1. Authentication (AuthN) â€” Who You Are
Purpose: Verify the identity of a user or system

Examples:
Username/password
Multi-factor authentication (MFA)
OAuth/OpenID Connect tokens
Key Point: Confirms identity, but does not determine permissions.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Authorization (AuthZ) â€” What You Can Access
Purpose: Determine permissions for a user/system after authentication
Examples:
Role-based access control (RBAC)
Attribute-based access control (ABAC)
ACLs (Access Control Lists)
Key Point: AuthZ happens after AuthN.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. SSL/TLS â€” Encrypt Data in Transit
SSL/TLS encrypts communication between clients and servers
Ensures:
Confidentiality â€“ data cannot be read by attackers
Integrity â€“ data not tampered
Authentication â€“ server identity verified via certificate
Example: HTTPS websites, secure API calls
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. mTLS (Mutual TLS) â€” Service-to-Service Trust
Mutual TLS extends TLS by authenticating both client and server
Used in microservices or service-to-service communication
Ensures:
Only trusted services can communicate
Encrypted communication
Example: Service A calls Service B securely, both verify each otherâ€™s certificate
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. SSDLC â€” Security in All Phases
Secure Software Development Life Cycle
Integrates security practices throughout development, not just at the end

Phases:
Requirements & Design â†’ threat modeling
Implementation â†’ secure coding, code reviews
Testing â†’ static/dynamic analysis, penetration testing
Deployment â†’ hardened configurations
Maintenance â†’ patching, monitoring
Goal: Build security by design, not as an afterthought

-----------------------------------------------------------------------
OAuth (Open Authorization)
Use Case: Grants third-party apps access to a user's resources without exposing passwords.

Example: A calendar app uses OAuth to access your Google Calendar.
Components:
Resource Owner: The user.
Client: The app requesting access.
Authorization Server: Issues tokens (e.g., Google, GitHub).
Resource Server: API/resource provider (e.g., Google Calendar API).
Does not handle authentication directly, though OpenID Connect (OIDC) builds on OAuth for that.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ðŸ“Œ SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language)
Use Case: Enterprise Single Sign-On (SSO).
Example: A corporate user logs into Salesforce via Microsoft Azure AD.
Components:
Identity Provider (IdP): Authenticates the user (e.g., Azure AD).
Service Provider (SP): The app the user wants to access (e.g., Salesforce).
SAML Assertion: XML document with user identity and attributes, digitally signed.
